{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564347"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:12:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:12:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16968"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16968"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.04,0.09,0.06,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9658"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16968"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85774"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4640"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"7951"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22780"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of quitting smoking. You notice a rash on his forearms which he then notes has been there for 3 weeks.  He reports mild fever and fatigue but is otherwise well. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He reports having unprotected sexual intercourse with multiple partners over the past six months.  His child attends day care, and he recently started bupropion for smoking cessation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a symmetrical non-itchy rash affecting his trunk, arms, and legs, including his palms and soles (Image). There is no mucosal involvement. Lymph node examination reveals generalised, non-tender lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Secondary syphilis","Guttate psoriasis","Drug eruption","Pityriasis rosea","Viral exanthem"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of secondary syphilis, which typically occurs 4-10 weeks after the primary chancre. The characteristic features include a symmetrical, red or copper-coloured, non-itchy maculopapular rash affecting the trunk and extremities, including palms and soles, accompanied by constitutional symptoms and generalised lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary syphilis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E bacteria and represents the systemic dissemination of the infection. The rash is highly infectious and typically resolves spontaneously within 2-6 weeks, even without treatment.  Knowledge of prevention with condoms can help prevent syphylis however it is still a world wide problem with over 8 million adults between 15 - 49 years acquiring syphilis (from 2022). The presence of palmoplantar involvement is particularly characteristic of secondary syphilis.  Patients typically present with a chancre (ulcer) on the labia or anus though this is not always seen as it heals within 10 days, and then secondary syphilis symptoms may present as above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPityriasis rosea\u003C/strong\u003E typically begins with a herald patch followed by a Christmas tree distribution of oval, salmon-coloured patches on the trunk. Unlike syphilis, it rarely affects palms and soles and is not associated with lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuttate psoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with small, drop-shaped, scaly plaques, often following a streptococcal throat infection. The lesions are typically more scaly and well-demarcated than those of secondary syphilis, and palmoplantar involvement is uncommon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral exanthem\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a more acute onset, often accompanied by more prominent systemic symptoms. The rash rarely involves palms and soles, and usually resolves within 1-2 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug eruption\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs within days to weeks of starting a new medication. While it can affect palms and soles, there is usually a clear temporal relationship with medication exposure, and the rash is often pruritic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary syphilis typically presents with a symmetrical, copper-coloured, non-itchy maculopapular rash affecting palms and soles.","The presence of palmoplantar involvement is a key distinguishing feature of secondary syphilis from other viral exanthems.","Risk factors and sexual history are crucial elements in diagnosing sexually transmitted infections."],"references":["Lopez P, Kwentoh I, Valdez Imbert M. A Peculiar Presentation of Syphilis as a Mysterious Rash: A Dermatological Dilemma. Cureus. 2023.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10504092/","World Health Organization. Syphilis. World Health Organization Fact Sheets. 2024. Available at: https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/syphilis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16968"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21295"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21295"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TDEEHPp666noTCtZPjvzGh0XE8pe2S.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TDEEHPp666noTCtZPjvzGh0XE8pe2S.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T17:32:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T17:32:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9658"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ